comments[2]{created_at,author,text}:
  "2026-07-12T13:35:11.977Z",maintainer-agent,"External sweep before implementation: no open PRs; zero open Dependabot, code-scanning, or secret-scanning alerts; pnpm audit reports no known vulnerabilities. @sentry/node 10.65.0 is available vs current 10.63.0, but dependency upgrades remain outside this measured hot-path change unless required by package API compatibility. Sentry still returns unresolved PM-CLI issues, so enabled capture/flush behavior must be preserved and reverified after the lazy-load change."
  "2026-07-12T15:42:07.246Z",maintainer-agent,"Completion evidence: @sentry/node is now loaded lazily through top-level createRequire only after telemetry disable guards; enabled init/capture/flush semantics remain covered. PM-linked Sentry tests passed 48/48. Live Sentry CLI access succeeded after the change; the local combined gate passed with critical=0 high=0, telemetry finish_error_rate_pct=0.25, and zero missing error-code rows. The observed workspace command baseline fell from roughly 1.2-2.0s reads before this tranche to 100k SDK list/get at 923/440ms and CLI operations 0.7-3.5s depending on query."
learnings[1]{created_at,author,text}:
  "2026-07-12T15:42:07.478Z",maintainer-agent,A static observability import can dominate every short-lived CLI command even when telemetry is disabled. Keeping external packaging unchanged while deferring the single module graph behind the existing opt-out gate preserves enabled telemetry without imposing its module-load cost on disabled runs.
